HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 750
By Atchley
A RESOLUTION to recognize Sevier County Mayor Larry Waters,
the longest-serving elected official in Tennessee,
on the occasion of his retirement.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should specially
recognize those Tennesseans who have performed with uncommon devotion and ability
throughout their careers in public service; and
WHEREAS, one such outstanding person is Sevier County Mayor Larry Waters, who is
taking a well-earned retirement in 2026 after a distinguished career that has spanned more than
five decades; and
WHEREAS, a lifelong resident of Sevier County, Larry Waters earned a Bachelor of
Science degree in Business Administration from the University of Tennessee in 1974; after
teaching for one year, he became a principal in the Sevier County school system; and
WHEREAS, in 1978, at the age of twenty-five, Mr. Waters ran for office and ultimately
became the youngest elected mayor in Tennessee; today, he holds the distinction of being the
State's longest-serving elected official, having played an important role in the incredible
transformation of his beloved Sevier County and the East Tennessee region over the past forty-
seven years; and
WHEREAS, under Mayor Waters's leadership, Sevier County has seen its population
more than triple, its operating budget grow nearly twentyfold, and its tourism industry expand to
welcome more than twenty-one million visitors annually, ranking the county among the top
tourism destinations in the Southeast; and
WHEREAS, his estimable mayoral tenure has included public safety and emergency
management improvements, the modernization of county government operations, coordinated
industrial recruitment and growth, and significant investment in education and economic
HJR0750
009448
- 1 -

development; he has also worked to build strong relationships between city, county, state, and
federal agencies, fostering collaboration and partnership across all levels of government; and
WHEREAS, during his decades of service, Mayor Waters has earned a reputation for
steady leadership during times of crisis and upheaval, including the devastating 2016 wildfires
and multiple periods of record-breaking tourism growth that required expanded infrastructure
and services; he has also been instrumental in advancing major capital projects, including the
expansion of the Sevier County Courthouse; and
WHEREAS, as the longest-serving county mayor in Tennessee history, Mayor Waters
has worked with generations of elected officials, community leaders, and citizens to shape
Sevier County's growth while protecting its character and sense of community; and
WHEREAS, through his ability to cast vision for the future, unify leaders, and manage
both tremendous growth and incredible challenges, Mayor Waters has effectively preserved and
advanced the collective interests of the citizens of Sevier County and their visitors; and
WHEREAS, his legacy was appropriately commemorated when the Tennessee County
Services Association named its Mayor of the Year Award in his honor and selected Larry
Waters as its inaugural recipient in 2023; and
WHEREAS, he has earned numerous other laurels, including the 2003 Pless R.
Newman Republican Services Award, the 2013 Boy Scouts Sequoyah District Great Smoky
Mountain Council Good Scout Award, and the 2010 Robert M. Wormsley Outstanding County
Official of the Year Award; he has been honored by East Tennessee State University (ETSU) as
an Honorary Alumnus and by the University of Tennessee as an Outstanding Alumnus; and
WHEREAS, Larry Waters has given back to his community far beyond his
accomplishments as Sevier County Mayor, having served in many leadership positions and
offices throughout his career, including with the United Way Campaign, Leadership Sevier and
Leadership Knoxville, Tennessee County Services Association, Tennessee Development
- 2 - 009448

District Association, East Tennessee Development District, East Tennessee Human Resources
Agency, Association of County Mayors of Tennessee, Tennessee Air Pollution Control Board,
Sevier County Republican Party, Tennessee Advisory Commission on Intergovernmental
Relations, East Tennessee Economic Development Agency, Sevier County Economic
Development Council, County Executives of America, and NACO Membership Committee; and
WHEREAS, passionate about the importance of education in producing a stronger and
more stable workforce and providing a higher quality of life in the region, Mayor Waters is a past
chairman and current member of the board of Carson-Newman Board of Trustees and has
served as chairman and executive of the University of Tennessee Chancellor's Associates; and
WHEREAS, as an organizer and founding member of the ETSU-Sevier County Health
Sciences Partnership, Mayor Waters played a significant role in founding The Sevier Center;
and
WHEREAS, Mr. Waters is an active member of the First Baptist Church of Gatlinburg,
having formerly served as chairman and currently serving as deacon; and
WHEREAS, a devoted family man, Larry Waters is most grateful for the love and support
of his wife, Terri, who has her own art studio in Gatlinburg; their son, David, who operates a
travel company locally and in two other states; their daughter, Adrienne, who is the first woman
to serve as circuit court judge in the Fourth Judicial District, and her husband, Bart Ogle; and
their grandchildren, Caden and Camilla Waters and Charlotte and Amelia Ogle; and
WHEREAS, this humble, caring man modestly asserts that "serving as Sevier County
Mayor has truly been the honor of a lifetime" and is grateful for the trust the people of Sevier
County have placed in him for the past forty-seven years; and
WHEREAS, Mayor Waters has announced that he will not be seeking reelection in 2026,
thus concluding a remarkable career of inspired leadership in service of Sevier County and the
East Tennessee region; and
- 3 - 009448

WHEREAS, Larry Waters has been a visionary in local and regional economic
development during his tenure as Sevier County Mayor, and he should be specially recognized
on this special occasion; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and commend Larry Waters, the longest-serving elected official
in Tennessee, upon his unprecedented tenure as Sevier County Mayor, salute his ongoing
commitment to his community and its progress, and extend to him our best wishes for a happy
and fulfilling retirement.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
